      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build and cook",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the {{olive-oil}} in a pan over medium heat. Fry the {{onion}}, {{carrot}}, and {{celery}} for 5 minutes. Add the {{garlic}}, {{tomato-puree}}, and {{oregano-dried}} and cook for 1 minute. Add the {{red-wine}} and let it bubble for 1 minute. Transfer to the slow cooker. Add the {{puy-lentils}}, {{tinned-tomatoes}}, {{stock-vegetable}}, {{thyme-fresh}}, {{bay-leaves}}, {{sea-salt-fine}}, and {{black-pepper}}. Cook on low for 6 to 8 hours, until the lentils are tender and have absorbed the sauce. Remove the {{thyme-fresh}} sprigs and {{bay-leaves}}. Taste and adjust seasoning.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Puy lentils (French green lentils) are the correct choice. Red lentils dissolve completely in 6 hours and produce a different dish entirely, more of a dal than a ragu",
              "cause": "Red lentils used rather than Puy",
              "symptom": "Lentils dissolved into the sauce rather than holding their shape"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add 100 ml hot stock and stir. The correct consistency for pasta sauce is thick but fluid. It should coat pasta, not clump around it",
              "cause": "Lentils absorbed all the liquid and then some",
              "symptom": "Sauce too thick and stodgy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Remove the lid and cook on high for 20 to 30 minutes to reduce. The sauce should look like bolognese, not soup",
              "cause": "Too much stock added, or lentils cooked less than expected",
              "symptom": "Sauce thin and watery after 6 hours"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Lentil bolognese is a batch-cook staple for households reducing meat consumption without reducing flavour. The slow cooker version is richer than the stovetop version because the lentils have hours to absorb the sauce fully. Use for pasta, lasagne, or served on toast with grated cheese.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
